5. Non-Functional Requirements and Design Decisions

Rather than discussing every non-functional requirement separately, this section focuses on the requirements that most strongly shaped the proposed REMS architecture. The most important concerns are auditability, confidentiality, usability, file versioning,
and timely notifications. These concerns directly influenced why the system is divided into separate components such as the Authentication and Authorisation component,  Application Management Service, Validation Service, Document Management and Versioning Service,
Notification Service, and Audit Trail Service.


NFR-01: Usability — Driving Responsibility Allocation

Usability is important because researchers may not be familiar with the ethics application process. The system should help users create, save, submit, revise, and track applications without needing constant help from administrators. This requirement affects both the
Web Interface and the backend design.

The REMS Web Interface is responsible for presenting dashboards, application forms, guidance panels, upload controls, validation messages, and status tracking information. However, it does not own the core business rules. The frontend should not decide whether an 
application is complete or whether it can move to the next status. Those decisions belong to the backend services.

This separation supports usability because the Web Interface can focus on clear presentation and user feedback. For example, if a researcher submits an incomplete application, the interface should show exactly which fields or sections are missing. This is supported 
by the Validation Service, which returns structured, field-level error information instead of a simple generic failure message.

The Validation Service is separated from the Application Management Service because validation rules may change over time. For example, the university may later add new mandatory fields or supporting document requirements. If validation logic is isolated, these changes
can be made without rewriting the whole application lifecycle. This also supports the requirement that completeness checking should be fast and understandable for users.

NFR-02: Confidentiality — Shaping the Access Architecture

Confidentiality is also a major design driver because ethics applications may contain sensitive research information, participant details, risk assessments, supporting documents, and feedback from reviewers or administrators. Not every user should be able to see or change 
every application. For example, a principal researcher should be able to create and submit their own application, but another unrelated researcher should not be able to access it.

To address this, the architecture places the Authentication and Authorisation component between the REMS Web Interface and the backend services. All requests from users must first pass through this component before reaching the Application Management Service, Document 
Management and Versioning Service, or any sensitive data. This creates a clear access-control boundary in the architecture.

The design uses a simple role-based access model. The main roles include principal researcher, authorised teammate, admin officer, reviewer, and system administrator. The principal researcher has the strongest control over their own application, including submission 
authority. Authorised teammates may be allowed to view, edit, or upload supporting documents, but they may not necessarily have permission to perform final submission. Admin officers and reviewers have access only to the applications relevant to their role.

This design keeps access control centralised instead of spreading permission checks across every part of the system. It also makes the architecture easier to reason about during review. If future versions of REMS add more user types, such as ethics committee members or 
external reviewers, the access model can be extended mainly within the Authentication and Authorisation component, rather than rewriting the whole application workflow.


NFR-03: Audit Trail — Most Constraining Requirement

Auditability is the most constraining non-functional requirement in this system because REMS handles formal ethics applications. The system must be able to show who performed an action, when the action happened, and what application or document was affected. Important 
actions include draft creation, auto-save, manual saving, document upload, submission, resubmission, revision updates, status changes, and access to sensitive application records.

This requirement affects the whole architecture because audit logging cannot be treated as an optional background feature. If an application status changes from “Draft” to “Submitted”, the system must also record the user identity and timestamp of that submission. If a 
document is uploaded, the system must record which user uploaded it, which application it belongs to, and when it was uploaded. Without this information, the system would not be reliable for compliance, review, or later dispute resolution.

For this reason, the architecture includes a dedicated Audit Trail Service. The Application Management Service triggers the Audit Trail Service whenever a significant state-changing action occurs. The audit record should be written as part of the same logical operation
as the application update. This means the application should not be successfully submitted if the audit record cannot be created. This design keeps the application state and audit history consistent.

An alternative design would be asynchronous audit logging, where audit events are placed into a queue and written later. This would make the main workflow faster and reduce coupling between components. However, it creates a risk that audit records could be delayed or
lost if the queue fails. For a compliance-related ethics system, this risk is not acceptable. Therefore, the chosen design prioritises correctness and traceability over maximum performance




NFR-04: File Versioning — Justifying the Document Management and Versioning Service

Ethics applications often include supporting documents, and these documents may be updated during the review or revision process. The system should not overwrite previous files because older versions may be needed for checking what was originally submitted, what was revised,
or what was available to reviewers at a particular time.

For this reason, the architecture includes a separate Document Management and Versioning Service. This component manages document uploads, file metadata, retrieval, and version history. When a researcher uploads a new version of a document, the old version should remain 
accessible instead of being replaced. Each document version should be linked to an application, uploader, upload timestamp, and version number.

The actual file content is stored in File/Object Storage, while document metadata is stored in the relational database. This separation is useful because files are usually larger and less structured than normal application records. The database can efficiently store and
search metadata, while file storage can manage the actual uploaded documents.

Keeping document versioning separate from the Application Management Service also reduces complexity. The Application Management Service only needs to coordinate the workflow, such as whether the application is in draft, submitted, under review, or revision requested.
The Document Management and Versioning Service is responsible for ensuring that file versions remain consistent and traceable.



NFR-05: Timely Notifications — Supporting Communication Without Blocking the Workflow

Timely notification is important because researchers need to know when something changes in their application. For example, they should be notified when an application is submitted successfully, when clarification is requested, when revision is required, or when a final
decision is made.

The architecture includes a dedicated Notification Service to handle this responsibility. This service creates in-system notifications and sends email notifications through an external email service. In-system notifications are important because REMS should remain the
official place where users check application status and feedback. Email is useful as an additional reminder, but it should not be treated as the official record.

This design avoids making the main application workflow depend too heavily on email delivery. Email services can be slow, unavailable, or unreliable. If the Application Management Service waited for email delivery before confirming a submission, the user experience 
could become poor. Therefore, the system should record the important application status and notification record inside REMS first, then allow email dispatch to happen separately.

This design supports both usability and reliability. Researchers receive reminders through email, but they can still log in to REMS to see the official status, feedback, and history even if an email is delayed or missed.



Overall Design Rationale

Overall, the proposed architecture separates responsibilities according to the main non-functional requirements. The Application Management Service acts as the central coordinator for the ethics application lifecycle, including creation, saving, submission, revision, resubmission,
and status updates. Around it, specialised components handle specific concerns: Authentication and Authorisation protects access, the Validation Service checks completeness, the Document Management and Versioning Service handles uploaded files and version history, the Notification Service manages user communication, and the Audit Trail Service records important actions.

This modular structure is more suitable than placing all responsibilities inside one large component. It makes the system easier to understand, test, maintain, and extend. It also makes the architecture more consistent with the REMS workflow, where sensitive applications
move through several states and require clear access control, traceability, document history, and communication with users.



